  Warning                                                         3900 1451   61
==================================================================3900 1451   62
  MF/MT combinations used to define ALL electron interaction data 3900 1451   63
  are newly defined MF/MT numbers for ENDF/B-VI that did not exist3900 1451   64
  in earlier versions of ENDF/B.                                  3900 1451   65
==================================================================3900 1451   66
  Definition of Data                                              3900 1451   67
==================================================================3900 1451   68
  Cross Sections (MF=23)                                          3900 1451   69
==================================================================3900 1451   70
1) The total electron interaction cross section is given          3900 1451   71
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/501. It is the sum of scatter,          3900 1451   72
   bremsstrahlung, excitation and ionization cross sections,      3900 1451   73
   i.e., MT = 526, 527, 528, and 534 through 572.                 3900 1451   74
2) The total electron ionization cross section is given           3900 1451   75
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/522. It is the sum of the aubshell      3900 1451   76
   cross sections, i.e., all MT = 534 through 572.                3900 1451   77
==================================================================3900 1451   78
  Angular and Energy Distributions (MF=26)                        3900 1451   79
==================================================================3900 1451   80
3) For Large Angle Scatter (MT=525), angular distributions of     3900 1451   81
   electrons are tabulated between cosine = -1.0 and 0.999999.    3900 1451   82
   Between +0.99999 and +1.0 it is analytically defined as        3900 1451   83
   Coulomb scattering,                                            3900 1451   84
                                                                  3900 1451   85
   d(sig)/d(cos) = A/[eta+(1.0 - cos)]^2                          3900 1451   86
                                                                  3900 1451   87
   where the shielding parameter (eta) is defined by the          3900 1451   88
   Steve Seltzer expression (see, ref. 1), and (A) is the         3900 1451   89
   normalization factor for the integral +0.99999 to +1.0.        3900 1451   90
   Electron elastic scatter means no energy loss, so only         3900 1451   91
   angular distributions are giving.                              3900 1451   92
4) For bremsstrahlung, both the outgoing electron and photon are  3900 1451   93
   described. The photon energy spectra are given, but angular    3900 1451   94
   distributions are not; these can be analytically defined by a  3900 1451   95
   number of different methods. For the electron, average energy  3900 1451   96
   loss is given. The electron is assumed to continue along its   3900 1451   97
   original direction of travel, so angular distributions are not 3900 1451   98
   given. WARNING - bremsstrahlung is a three body process,       3900 1451   99
   involving an electron, a photon, and an atom - so that you     3900 1451  100
   cannot use energy or momentum correlation to simply relate     3900 1451  101
   the secondary electron and the emitted photon.                 3900 1451  102
5) For excitation, the average energy loss of the electron is     3900 1451  103
   given. The electron is assumed to continue along its original  3900 1451  104
   direction of travel, so angular distributions are not given.   3900 1451  105
6) For Ionization, the spectra of electrons is given. The electron3900 1451  106
   is assumed to continue along its original direction of travel, 3900 1451  107
   so angular distributions are not given. In ionization two      3900 1451  108
   identical electrons emerge; the incident electron, and an      3900 1451  109
   electron ejected by the atom [thereby ionizing the atom]. Since3900 1451  110
   the two particles are indistinquishable, we define the electron3900 1451  111
   with the lower energy to be that ejected by the atom, and the  3900 1451  112
   electron with the higher energy to be the incident electron.   3900 1451  113
   The energy of the two electrons is exactly correlated by energy3900 1451  114
   conservation: initial incident electron energy = binding energy3900 1451  115
   of the ejected electron, plus the kinetic energy of the ejected3900 1451  116
   and the secondary incident electron. Therefore only the spectra3900 1451  117
   of the lower energy, ejected electron is given. The energy of  3900 1451  118
   the secondary incident electron should be defined to conserve  3900 1451  119
   energy, as described above. The energy lost by the incident    3900 1451  120
   electron is the sum of the binding and kinetic energy of the   3900 1451  121
   ejected electron.                                              3900 1451  122
7) Relaxation of ionized atoms back to neutrality is not described3900 1451  123
   here; it is described in the companion Evaluated Atomic Data   3900 1451  124
   Library (EADL).                                                3900 1451  125
